attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a sophisticated Linux backdoor or Remote Access Trojan (RAT). It exhibits several high-confidence malicious behaviors: 1) Masquerading: It attempts to hide its presence by overwriting its process name to '/sbin/auditd' (sub_402384). 2) Persistence: It contains logic to install itself as a systemd service by writing unit files to '/usr/lib/systemd/system/' and creating symlinks in 'multi-user.target.wants' (sub_417d91). 3) Anti-Forensics: It clears the 'HISTFILE' environment variable to prevent command logging (sub_42233e). 4) Remote Access: The sample allocates pseudo-terminals (/dev/ptmx, /dev/pts/%d) and spawns interactive shells (/bin/bash, /bin/sh), which is typical for remote shell capabilities (sub_4bc16d, sub_4bd723). 5) Advanced Networking: It utilizes the KCP protocol (ikcp.cpp) for reliable, low-latency communication, often used by modern malware to bypass standard network filtering.
